<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="49" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1078,2009]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1258,1283]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[352,406,1259,1283]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Tube</emphasis>
: white opaque, about 0.8 mm in diameter (portion shown in 
<figureCitation box="[1097,1164,1258,1282]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1811,1834]" captionTargetBox="[315,1281,652,1749]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[281,1291,628,1759]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Line drawings of Bathyvermilia challengeri. HURL specimen, BPBM Acc. No. 1983.252; A, B—tubes, C—operculum, D—collar and thoracic membranes, E, F—collar chaetae, G— Apomatus chaeta, H—abdominal chaeta, I—thoracic uncinus in profile view, J—anterior abdominal uncinus in profile view, K—posterior abdominal uncinus in frontal view, Lposterior abdomen with pygidium. Scale: A— 0.5 mm, B— 0.5 mm, C— 0.25 mm, D— 0.1 mm, E— 2 µm, F— 5 µm, G— 5 µm, H— 2 µm, I— 2 µm, J— 2 µm, K— 2 µm, L— 0.15 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203388/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number box="[1149,1164,1258,1282]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B 
<quantity box="[1225,1305,1258,1282]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="27.0">27 mm</quantity>
long), with very regularly closely arranged smooth transverse ridges; longitudinal groove cutting transverse ridges (
<figureCitation box="[1340,1410,1295,1319]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1811,1834]" captionTargetBox="[315,1281,652,1749]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[281,1291,628,1759]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Line drawings of Bathyvermilia challengeri. HURL specimen, BPBM Acc. No. 1983.252; A, B—tubes, C—operculum, D—collar and thoracic membranes, E, F—collar chaetae, G— Apomatus chaeta, H—abdominal chaeta, I—thoracic uncinus in profile view, J—anterior abdominal uncinus in profile view, K—posterior abdominal uncinus in frontal view, Lposterior abdomen with pygidium. Scale: A— 0.5 mm, B— 0.5 mm, C— 0.25 mm, D— 0.1 mm, E— 2 µm, F— 5 µm, G— 5 µm, H— 2 µm, I— 2 µm, J— 2 µm, K— 2 µm, L— 0.15 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203388/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number box="[1395,1410,1295,1319]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1078,2009]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis box="[197,384,1367,1391]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Branchial crown</emphasis>
: with ten pairs of radioles not joined by inter-radiolar membrane. Branchial eyes not visible in preserved material. Stylodes absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1078,2009]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis box="[197,301,1441,1465]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Peduncle</emphasis>
: inserted as dorsal 
<number box="[518,532,1441,1465]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" value="2.0">2</number>
nd radiole, about same thickness as rest of radioles, smooth, circular in cross-section (
<figureCitation box="[210,279,1477,1501]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1811,1834]" captionTargetBox="[315,1281,652,1749]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[281,1291,628,1759]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Line drawings of Bathyvermilia challengeri. HURL specimen, BPBM Acc. No. 1983.252; A, B—tubes, C—operculum, D—collar and thoracic membranes, E, F—collar chaetae, G— Apomatus chaeta, H—abdominal chaeta, I—thoracic uncinus in profile view, J—anterior abdominal uncinus in profile view, K—posterior abdominal uncinus in frontal view, Lposterior abdomen with pygidium. Scale: A— 0.5 mm, B— 0.5 mm, C— 0.25 mm, D— 0.1 mm, E— 2 µm, F— 5 µm, G— 5 µm, H— 2 µm, I— 2 µm, J— 2 µm, K— 2 µm, L— 0.15 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203388/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number box="[263,279,1477,1501]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
C); slightly enlarged at base of operculum; constriction present. Pair of lateral wings proximal to opercular bulb and pseudoperculum absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1078,2009]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis box="[197,322,1550,1574]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Operculum</emphasis>
: inverted conical, slightly longer than wide, with simple almost flat calcareous distal plate (
<figureCitation box="[1342,1409,1549,1573]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1811,1834]" captionTargetBox="[315,1281,652,1749]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[281,1291,628,1759]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Line drawings of Bathyvermilia challengeri. HURL specimen, BPBM Acc. No. 1983.252; A, B—tubes, C—operculum, D—collar and thoracic membranes, E, F—collar chaetae, G— Apomatus chaeta, H—abdominal chaeta, I—thoracic uncinus in profile view, J—anterior abdominal uncinus in profile view, K—posterior abdominal uncinus in frontal view, Lposterior abdomen with pygidium. Scale: A— 0.5 mm, B— 0.5 mm, C— 0.25 mm, D— 0.1 mm, E— 2 µm, F— 5 µm, G— 5 µm, H— 2 µm, I— 2 µm, J— 2 µm, K— 2 µm, L— 0.15 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203388/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number box="[1394,1409,1549,1573]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
C) about 
<quantity box="[220,285,1585,1609]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in diameter (specimen from Stn. 
<number box="[659,715,1585,1609]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" value="6334.0">6334</number>
with a calcareous granule inside operculum).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1078,2009]" box="[197,1294,1621,1648]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis box="[197,555,1624,1648]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Collar and thoracic membranes</emphasis>
: collar trilobed. Thoracic membranes reaching up to 
<number box="[1152,1166,1624,1648]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" value="4.0">4</number>
th chaetiger.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1078,2009]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis box="[197,278,1660,1684]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="49">Thorax</emphasis>
: with seven thoracic chaetigers, six of which uncinigerous (
